title: ECS clickstream-derived attributes
description:
Attributes Present in this table (as of mid-March, 2021):

- tax_article_sku_recommended: "attribute_value" column in this case contains all sku_recommended values for which the event had a lower(scope_area) = '%articles%' and for which sku_recommended is not null. Values are parsed out using either colon or pipe delimiter, de-duped, and inserted into this table with a granularity of one row per unique combination of: tax_year/visitor_session_id/sku_recommended value. Other table columns are populated using data from the FIRST event in the session on which that particular sku_recommended value was seen.

- aam_segment_ids_session: "attribute_value" column in this case contains all aam_segment_ids values parsed (using colon or pipe delimiters), de-duped, and re-concatenated together using pipes into a single distinct list per: tax_year, visitor_Session_id, AND auth/pseudonym_id. Most other column values are not populated for this attribute, since they represent "per-event" values and are thus not available for rows in which data has been pre-aggregated to this level of session-auth-ty.

- aam_segment_ids_entry: "attribute_value" column in this case contains all aam_segment_ids values from the FIRST, PAGE-VIEW type of event during the session. Row-level granularity is one row per tax_year & visitor_session_id. Values are parsed (using colon or pipe delimiters), de-duped (in case the same ID is passed more than once on that single first page view event) and re-concatenated together using pipes.

title: Authenticated Credit Campaign
description:
The list of campaigns which are credited with bringing the authenticated user back to the Turbo Tax platform for the given tax year.

/**
 * 
 * 1. Take the Intuit user authentication records for the platform (auth_id) and find the first 
 *    authentication that happened for each user in the tax season (ex. TY 2019).
 * 
 * 2. Now find all the user's devices (ivids) associated with the user across all sessions both 
 *    prior to the first login and after the first login (logged in session or not: this includes 
 *    all sessions).
 * 
 * 3. Find the session closest in time to the first login which has a campaign associated
 *    to the session.  The session could be related to the device the user first authenticated on
 *    or could be related to a session on a different device.  The session MUST be within a 30 day
 *    window prior to the first login, and no older. If no session with campaign found, assign a "non-campaign"
 *    attribution from the login session.
 * 
 * 4. Finally, the end result should be a single row for each unique user on the Intuit platform which
 *    contains the first authentication along with the first session related to the authentication with
 *    an associated campaign
 *
 * NOTE: Any session with campaign information older than 30 days from the first login session date 
 *       is filtered out of the result set.  There will be only a single entry per auth_id which MAY
 *       include a visit (session) with campaign information within 30 day window prior to first 
 *       authentication. All other records are filtered.  As new information comes in, i.e. user logs
 *       in on a phone which had a session prior to the "first login for tax season", we fully expect
 *       campaign attribution (credit) to change since the phone may have been used to click a campaign
 *       link before the user signed in on another device.  Later information can change the outcome
 *       of campaign attribution.
 *
 * in: auth_session_global, visitor_session_global
 * out: sub_auth_credit_campaign
 * 
 */

https://wiki.intuit.com/display/IDataEng/sub_auth_credit_campaign

title: Request Uuid Info Clickstream Global
description: This is a stage table used to copy the elements which could solely be sourced from the new ECS clickstream over to Vertica, where it's used in a sql script to derive the final target table: tax_src.request_uuid_info. That table contains data pertaining to data import requests for the TurboTax W2 form. This table is a replacement for the legacy table in Vertica ctg_analyst_layer schema by the same name. This new table contains data only for TY20 onward. The "device_type" column in the legacy table is missing form the new table because it DNE in the Segment clickstream. "platform" is not in the legacy table but was added to the new table to help compensate for missing device_type. "ua" column in the legacy table was renamed "user_agent_id" in the new table and is now an alphanumeric hashkey (instead of an int) used for joining to the tax_src.dim_user_agent_global table. "Reviewed Flag" is always true/equal to "1" because of known need to deprecate (what this used to represent to the business is no longer relevant because the experience changed).

title: Authentication Identifier Mapping
description:
Content

The global_auth_id_mapping table contains a mapping between an auth_id and a pseudonym_id.  This data is partitioned over tax year.

Source

The source data for global auth id mapping come from two thrive tables:

  1. cg_nueet_account_auth_log_eve

  2. cg_nueet_account_auth_log_oa

The tables are located here:

s3:/idl-thrive-uw2-processing-cto-prd/warehouse.parquet/thrive_dwh.db

For more information on Thrive please visit:

https://github.intuit.com/data-process/thrive

For more information on nueet please visit:

NUEET redesign - Target State

For more information on nueet auth logs, please visit:

https://github.intuit.com/data-process/thrive-artifacts/tree/develop/artifacts/cg_nueet_account_auth_log_eve

https://github.intuit.com/data-process/thrive-artifacts/tree/develop/artifacts/cg_nueet_account_auth_log_oa

ETL

Upon each adobe feed translator run, the global_auth_id_mapping job does a union between the two thrive tables (cg_nueet_account_auth_log_eve and cg_nueet_account_auth_log_oa) and the existing global_auth_id_mapping table to produce all the unique pairs of auth_id and pseudonym_id.  This table retains up to the day information regarding this relationship for the tax year.

Usage

This table should be used to correlate an auth_id with a pseudonym_id or a pseudonym_id with an auth_id.

title: TTO Fuego Completeness Graph V2 responses
description:
Intent: This table was created to help understand a TTO customer topic completion rate and could be joined with CAT POR based data to understand if topic data ended up on a filed tax return. 


Data Source: The data is sourced from FUEGO completeness graph v2 responses generated throughout a customer's TTO tax prep experience. These graphs identifies whcih form-fileds are complete and which are incomplete for the given Job in the FUEGO topic. This drives TTO user experience through a topic (called inbetween screns) and also during review experiences such as Complete Check (i.e., next screen/question, what is missing). 


Notes:

- Completeness Graph V2 response data collection began Feb 2021

- Data does not contain actual values user entered

- Not all TTO topics are on FUEGO, not all FUEGO topics have completeness graphs, and not all completeness graphs v1 have been migrated to v2

- Form-Field data in reponse is based on TKE but CAT is based on TPS. A mapping file is available to bridge the two formats

- Points of contact: Irene Ma (Analyst), Ravichandra Kancharla (DE), Ravi Pillala (DE), Marty Lewandowski (Product Engineering), Eric Sacks (PM), Young Yuk (PM) 

- Data is not SLA bound

title: Visit Page Num
description:
In prior (Adobe-sourced) version of fact_clickstream_psd, this visit_page_num column was a result of Adobe's processing. It's actually a count of hits associated to the visitor in the current session not a count of pages. (Meaning it also incremented for click/track type events).

ECS received_sequence_number (defined here: https://github.intuit.com/data-process/ecs-hive-schema/blob/develop/hive/clickstream_dwh/ecs_clickstream_turbotax/prd/create_table.hql#L334) is not a direct equivalent to the Adobe visit_page_num property, but it's close. The main difference between ECS and Adobe here will be that ECS sessionizes across all products, and I believe counts all types of events (Adobe only counted track and page events) and so the "received_sequence_number" for events in a session will sometimes skip numbers due to a visitor leaving TurboTax, or due to events like "identify", "group", "alias" that aren't relevant for clickstream analysis.

title: Language

For example: "en-us" versus "English (United States)".

title: Rad Flag
description: Boolean flag indicating whether the user is part of the RAD (Refund Advance) program Little nuance: If a user created a Turbo card account but got rejected at final qualification in the underwriting, then they will have a non RAD Turbo Card with all the RAD card features such as $0 fee etc. just not the loan itself. And their rad_flag will still be true. One way to differentiate them is to use init_fund_amt. The loan amounts are within fixed tiers for example for ty20 there are 10 tiers: 250,500,750,1000,1500,2000,2500,3000,3500,4000. If a user has null or some other number as init_fund_amt, then he/she might be the rejected case.

title: First Non Empty Campaign

Since we the absence of campaign is treated as "non-campaign" campaign, we're effectively storing the campaign value for the first event in a session.

title: First Campaign
description: First campaign is calculated by looking for the first campaign reference within first 60 seconds of a session. If it is not foud, a special "Non-campaign" value is assigned. See @tax_src.fact_clickstream_psd to understand how a campaign reference is computed for every event. This field is a struct with fields: id - campaign id from @tax_src.dim_campaign_global table timestamp - epoch timestam associated with the event holding campaign event_id - of the even with campaign value screen - on which campaign was captured page_url - on which campaign was captured page_url_id - ref to @tax_src.dim_page_url_global referrer_url - referrer when campaign was captured referrer_url_id - ref to @tax_src.dim_page_url_global site_area_id - ref to @tax_src.dim_site_area_global
